1
00:00:02,410 --> 00:00:03,071
Bionic.

2
00:00:05,934 --> 00:00:06,836
Straight from the heart.

3
00:00:08,237 --> 00:00:11,743
This talk is straight from the heart.

4
00:00:11,762 --> 00:00:14,666
I shall start in my usual way.

5
00:00:14,686 --> 00:00:30,730
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudasa

6
00:00:31,452 --> 00:00:48,570
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

7
00:00:49,831 --> 00:00:53,475
The Buddha's teaching is a mandala.

8
00:00:53,494 --> 00:00:56,838
It doesn't matter at which point you enter it.

9
00:00:56,859 --> 00:00:59,180
You end up touching all part of its petals.

10
00:00:59,902 --> 00:01:04,328
and somewhere along the line you touch sort of base.

11
00:01:04,349 --> 00:01:05,950
It's sort of one whole teaching.

12
00:01:05,990 --> 00:01:08,453
It sort of makes sense in the whole.

13
00:01:08,474 --> 00:01:15,483
And just occasionally I allow myself just to wander around and see where it takes me.

14
00:01:17,064 --> 00:01:23,072
So my entrance point is this little word which is central to the Buddha's teaching, dukkha.

15
00:01:24,795 --> 00:01:27,278
This word dukkha is...

16
00:01:28,691 --> 00:01:58,242
it has various etymologies put to it the roots where it comes from one of the strangest ones I think because in those days the early commentators were creative in their etymology if a word sounded like something else it must have its root there so one of the things is an axle and the rod which goes into the bracket doesn't fit properly

17
00:01:59,454 --> 00:02:00,715
You get that?

18
00:02:01,037 --> 00:02:03,338
It's not, you get that crunch.

19
00:02:04,939 --> 00:02:14,469
But the one that's sort of most obvious is just a hard space or a hard place.

20
00:02:14,490 --> 00:02:20,355
So, what the Buddha is saying is that this life is a hard place.

21
00:02:21,776 --> 00:02:27,943
And if he had left it at that, we'd have been stuck in the

22
00:02:28,462 --> 00:02:58,064
existential horror of just being in a hard place and not being able to make much sense of it but through his own investigations he discovered at least the psychological cause for it the deeper causes but at least the psychological cause which we translate slightly badly as desire and then of course the announcement that there is an end to it there is an end to dukkha it is possible to come to an end to dukkha

23
00:02:58,753 --> 00:03:03,039
which is not annihilation, by the way.

24
00:03:03,060 --> 00:03:06,663
So what does he mean by dukkha, this word of a hard place?

25
00:03:08,447 --> 00:03:15,695
Well, the first one is rather comically called dukkha-dukkha, which means just the suffering of ordinary suffering.

26
00:03:16,377 --> 00:03:18,900
And I think I don't have to go into that too deeply.

27
00:03:20,442 --> 00:03:24,387
That's just the pains in the body, the emotional states we come across.

28
00:03:25,248 --> 00:03:28,693
Even these pains in the body are not, strictly speaking,

29
00:03:29,027 --> 00:03:32,352
what he's referring to as dukkha, although they are unpleasant.

30
00:03:34,713 --> 00:03:47,068
And these emotional states that we get into, these mental states, have their root cause in some sort of wrong view.

31
00:03:49,031 --> 00:03:50,472
We aren't seeing things properly.

32
00:03:50,832 --> 00:03:53,215
We don't have a right perspective.

33
00:03:53,235 --> 00:03:57,280
And this perspective causes us to form wrong relationships.

34
00:03:57,748 --> 00:04:06,639
And that wrong relationship includes within it a whole set of emotional responses which we end up as conditioning.

35
00:04:07,602 --> 00:04:13,209
These emotional responses, because we can't find our way out of them, reinforce the original wrong view.

36
00:04:14,991 --> 00:04:17,194
So we're getting up in this cycle.

37
00:04:18,014 --> 00:04:23,021
And this cycle of going round and round, that's the root meaning of the word karma.

38
00:04:23,041 --> 00:04:24,903
That's what we mean in Buddhism by karma.

39
00:04:26,098 --> 00:04:30,182
It's not, strictly speaking, you say what happens to you on the outside.

40
00:04:31,723 --> 00:04:33,185
You can also call that karma.

41
00:04:33,925 --> 00:04:43,535
But in terms of what we're trying to do, which is come to the end of suffering, this karma that the Buddha is referring to is these cycles within our own head.

42
00:04:45,776 --> 00:04:53,163
These cycles within our own head, of course, are then projected onto the world and we keep recreating similar situations.

43
00:04:54,985 --> 00:04:56,105
And through our dullness,

44
00:04:56,473 --> 00:04:58,357
We blame the other.

45
00:04:59,517 --> 00:05:03,043
It's got to be my parents.

46
00:05:03,064 --> 00:05:06,148
I would never have ended up like this were it not for my mother.

47
00:05:06,988 --> 00:05:08,512
Comes in for a lot of sticks, poor mother.

48
00:05:09,692 --> 00:05:13,619
And then there's society, education, educators.

49
00:05:13,819 --> 00:05:14,761
Oh my goodness.

50
00:05:14,781 --> 00:05:18,026
Everybody has caused me this dreadful suffering.

51
00:05:19,767 --> 00:05:24,355
So this sense of ordinary dukkha, this sense of ordinary suffering,

52
00:05:26,139 --> 00:05:29,023
as its root cause in some sort of wrong view.

53
00:05:29,382 --> 00:05:30,704
We're not seeing things properly.

54
00:05:31,946 --> 00:05:33,127
We'll come to that in time.

55
00:05:35,790 --> 00:05:42,516
And our meditation is concerned with undermining that whole process.

56
00:05:43,197 --> 00:05:45,600
And that's what we're doing when we practice Vipassana.

57
00:05:46,880 --> 00:05:50,064
Vipassana is not simply a correction of view.

58
00:05:50,245 --> 00:05:52,206
That's its actual main point.

59
00:05:53,028 --> 00:05:54,408
But

60
00:05:55,132 --> 00:06:03,783
Fortunately, as one of the gifts of vipassana, the purification of the heart takes place of its own.

61
00:06:04,204 --> 00:06:08,151
You don't have to do anything to purify the heart.

62
00:06:08,170 --> 00:06:14,639
In fact, if you try to purify your heart, then it's a bit like the blind leading the blind.

63
00:06:15,661 --> 00:06:21,228
It's the very deluded part of ourselves which is trying to do something about the effects of its own delusion.

64
00:06:22,370 --> 00:06:23,872
And you just end up being in a mess.

65
00:06:25,422 --> 00:06:33,617
So when we're sitting here and this dukkha, these mental states arise, what possibilities have you got?

66
00:06:34,016 --> 00:06:36,380
What can you do about them?

67
00:06:36,482 --> 00:06:42,451
One side, of course, is to suppress it, to turn away from it, turn your attention somewhere else.

68
00:06:42,471 --> 00:06:45,057
If you feel lonely, turn the TV on.

69
00:06:45,336 --> 00:06:47,901
Easy enough.

70
00:06:47,922 --> 00:06:49,084
But it's there, you see.

71
00:06:49,283 --> 00:06:50,865
It's a conditioning within the mind.

72
00:06:50,925 --> 00:06:53,148
You can't, that hasn't been dealt with.

73
00:06:53,408 --> 00:06:55,672
So we know that from our own Western psychology.

74
00:06:56,392 --> 00:07:00,338
And it sits there, just bubbling away, boiling away, burning, burning.

75
00:07:00,418 --> 00:07:03,221
This is the Buddha's old expression of burning.

76
00:07:05,345 --> 00:07:10,372
And the only other side is to indulge it.

77
00:07:11,713 --> 00:07:14,158
If you indulge loneliness, you get into self-pity.

78
00:07:14,858 --> 00:07:15,538
Why me?

79
00:07:16,560 --> 00:07:16,641
Hmm?

80
00:07:17,346 --> 00:07:21,434
And that self-pity simply fuels that sense of loneliness more and more.

81
00:07:24,178 --> 00:07:33,255
Eventually you end up on Westminster Bridge or Worth, Prozac.

82
00:07:33,276 --> 00:07:41,750
So here we are, we're stuck with a feeling of me wanting to do something about myself.

83
00:07:43,250 --> 00:07:50,476
And as soon as I want to do something about myself, as soon as I want to change myself, I have to engage in this state of mind.

84
00:07:51,718 --> 00:07:54,139
This engagement leaves me with two options.

85
00:07:54,160 --> 00:08:03,187
I can either suppress it, try to destroy it, kill it, turn away from it, ignore it, or try and do something about it and get involved in it.

86
00:08:06,791 --> 00:08:11,875
Both sides will begin to realize they're actually going to cause more suffering.

87
00:08:11,896 --> 00:08:12,497
More suffering.

88
00:08:16,240 --> 00:08:20,404
Through the Vipassana we discover this third position.

89
00:08:20,985 --> 00:08:31,158
If you imagine a triangle and the base is this suppression, indulgence, suppression, indulgence, suppression, indulgence, creating this vicious circle.

90
00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:37,807
And at the top of the triangle or the cone, perhaps the circle of the cone, that's good, I never thought of that.

91
00:08:37,826 --> 00:08:38,307
Yeah, that's good.

92
00:08:38,727 --> 00:08:41,610
The vicious circle at the base of the cone.

93
00:08:44,735 --> 00:08:45,336
That's a good one.

94
00:08:46,177 --> 00:08:58,129
And as you climb up the cone, as you lift yourself out of that involvement with what the heart is presenting you, you're discovering a transcendental position.

95
00:08:58,309 --> 00:09:01,332
It's transcendent of this game, of this play.

96
00:09:03,014 --> 00:09:03,755
It's transcendent.

97
00:09:04,197 --> 00:09:09,221
Because now you're able to discover a place where you're looking at something.

98
00:09:09,241 --> 00:09:11,104
You're no longer involved in it.

99
00:09:13,936 --> 00:09:28,433
When you shift your consciousness to that point, when you lift yourself up to become the onlooker, the experiencer of what is going on inside you, you've discovered a different level of consciousness.

100
00:09:28,453 --> 00:09:33,581
It's not the same as a consciousness which considers itself to be emotional.

101
00:09:35,001 --> 00:09:35,743
I am happy.

102
00:09:36,063 --> 00:09:36,764
I am sad.

103
00:09:38,086 --> 00:09:40,109
It's not the same as a thought consciousness.

104
00:09:40,288 --> 00:09:41,630
I think something like that.

105
00:09:42,672 --> 00:09:43,452
Therefore I am.

106
00:09:43,855 --> 00:10:12,546
and it's not the same as a body consciousness I am this body it's something which is shall we say transcendent of all that discovering a position where it objectifies it turns into an object everything that previously in our lives we've experienced as a subject this is me soon as we do that you see we have as it were discovered

107
00:10:13,724 --> 00:10:18,649
the understanding of anatta, this very difficult doctrine of not-self.

108
00:10:19,830 --> 00:10:26,317
Now, when the Buddha talks about not-self, that's not a philosophical or metaphysical position.

109
00:10:26,437 --> 00:10:27,958
He's not saying there is no self.

110
00:10:29,721 --> 00:10:36,447
If he were in his day to say there is no self, then he would have been in this constant argument with people who said that there were.

111
00:10:37,187 --> 00:10:38,089
He didn't have to argue.

112
00:10:39,671 --> 00:10:43,495
The anatta doctrine, the doctrine of not-self, is just a

113
00:10:43,761 --> 00:10:55,941
skillful tool with which whatever you experience, whatever you experience, within yourself or without yourself, can be looked at and you can say, well, this is not me.

114
00:10:58,264 --> 00:11:00,388
This is not me.

115
00:11:01,529 --> 00:11:04,495
Which doesn't deny the fact that there may be something.

116
00:11:04,836 --> 00:11:06,899
We'll come to that in a bit.

117
00:11:06,918 --> 00:11:10,764
It's just a very skillful tool in which we can say, well, this is not me.

118
00:11:12,482 --> 00:11:15,666
And that's the purpose of accessing that level of consciousness.

119
00:11:16,506 --> 00:11:35,024
Because every time you experience something, a pain in the knee, so you can look at it, you can feel it, you can sense it, and because of that distance you've created, because you haven't fallen into the error of suppressing it, turning away from it, I don't want to feel this, or indulging it, oh, my knee, all that sort of stuff.

120
00:11:35,765 --> 00:11:40,971
Because you're there, just feeling, sensing, experiencing the pain, you see,

121
00:11:42,638 --> 00:11:43,278
It's an object.

122
00:11:43,359 --> 00:11:44,440
You're looking at it.

123
00:11:44,460 --> 00:11:46,782
If it's an object, it can't be the subject.

124
00:11:46,902 --> 00:11:50,325
It's as simple as that.

125
00:11:50,345 --> 00:11:58,793
Even though I say it's as simple as that, when the pain gets too heavy, of course, if you feel that your knee is just about to explode, all that lovely doctrine disappears.

126
00:12:02,136 --> 00:12:11,024
This not self-business takes us so far, but when it comes to the hard point, then we immediately collapse into the old

127
00:12:11,562 --> 00:12:14,764
level of consciousness of being a human being.

128
00:12:23,774 --> 00:12:30,039
Level of consciousness here, not to be confused with a state of mind.

129
00:12:31,160 --> 00:12:35,304
What I'm referring, the word in the Pali for some of you know is citta.

130
00:12:35,845 --> 00:12:39,948
So, a state of mind is, you know, whether you're happy, whether you're sad,

131
00:12:40,552 --> 00:12:44,476
the thoughts that go around that, the physical feelings that arise with that.

132
00:12:44,777 --> 00:12:48,500
All that, you can say, is a sort of state, a state of mind, you can say.

133
00:12:49,721 --> 00:12:53,365
A level of consciousness is concerned with how we understand things.

134
00:12:54,927 --> 00:13:05,118
So one of the obvious leaps of consciousness that happens to the vast majority of human beings happens to us around about the age of seven.

135
00:13:05,138 --> 00:13:07,720
So two important things happen to us around about the age of seven.

136
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,222
First of all, we shift from an

137
00:13:10,607 --> 00:13:39,788
a universe which has no basic moral laws to one in which suddenly there is right and wrong so this is the truth or the truth within the myth of the Garden of Eden and the other thing of course is that we stop believing in our imagination as being real it has to be reality tested so that's why now we are in this pitiful situation

138
00:13:40,256 --> 00:13:49,528
of being unable to believe that Father Christmas will come down that chimney and present as a present.

139
00:13:49,548 --> 00:13:50,408
Which is sad, isn't it?

140
00:13:51,129 --> 00:13:56,174
I mean, those magic days, they've all gone, they've disappeared.

141
00:13:56,215 --> 00:13:59,359
We now live in this rather terrible reality.

142
00:14:00,519 --> 00:14:08,830
So that shift, you see, is a change in the way that young consciousness understands and sees the world.

143
00:14:10,379 --> 00:14:22,294
So when the Buddha's talking about the process of awakening, in our language, in our terminology, it is a movement within consciousness itself.

144
00:14:22,315 --> 00:14:26,961
Because the root problem lies in consciousness itself.

145
00:14:26,981 --> 00:14:32,249
It's consciousness itself that knows which doesn't know properly.

146
00:14:35,033 --> 00:14:38,277
And that's why it's so difficult for us to awaken.

147
00:14:39,893 --> 00:14:45,557
Because that which is trying to awaken is that which is deluded.

148
00:14:45,577 --> 00:14:49,881
And the whole definition of delusion is that you don't know where the delusion is.

149
00:14:50,482 --> 00:14:52,585
If you knew where the delusion was, then you wouldn't be deluded.

150
00:14:54,907 --> 00:15:01,873
So here's the Buddha with his very clever teaching saying, listen, don't worry about who you are.

151
00:15:02,614 --> 00:15:06,998
You don't get involved in that question as who you are, but who you are not.

152
00:15:08,192 --> 00:15:37,052
if you can find who you are not eventually you should end up finding out who you are so the doctrine of anatta the doctrine of not-self is a teaching tool it's not a philosophical statement in which in our meditation through the process of distancing from what we experience that little distance which objectifies what we're looking at right is taking us backwards so we're not the body

153
00:15:37,724 --> 00:16:05,605
we're not the emotion we're not thought and then we're stuck with this I must be the thinker the knower the witness you see so now we make that final mistake of thinking that we are that consciousness itself the mistake there is one of shall we say a mirror

154
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:12,389
When you look at your face in the mirror generally speaking you believe that's how people see you.

155
00:16:14,851 --> 00:16:15,513
Big mistake, huh?

156
00:16:16,235 --> 00:16:17,756
Because they see your face the other way around.

157
00:16:18,979 --> 00:16:22,144
And it's only when you use two mirrors do you realize how big your ears are.

158
00:16:25,909 --> 00:16:27,511
I was very upset with my sister.

159
00:16:27,552 --> 00:16:33,561
I was surprised at the size of my ears when I cut my hair off.

160
00:16:33,581 --> 00:16:34,663
It can hurt, you know.

161
00:16:37,528 --> 00:16:43,196
So it's coming to recognize that what we see in the mirror isn't actually what people see.

162
00:16:46,059 --> 00:16:52,048
Now, when this knowing, this awareness, I'm just using the word consciousness, yeah?

163
00:16:52,428 --> 00:16:55,732
Just, you know, awareness, there's many words for it.

164
00:16:56,133 --> 00:16:59,337
Sense of being, sense of presence, the now.

165
00:16:59,937 --> 00:17:05,005
There's all sorts of ways that writers try to explain this level because it's...

166
00:17:05,743 --> 00:17:07,486
It doesn't happen in our language.

167
00:17:07,506 --> 00:17:10,028
We don't have an actual word for it, in a sense.

168
00:17:11,349 --> 00:17:15,134
The closest we get to it is intuitive intelligence and intuition.

169
00:17:18,238 --> 00:17:25,707
When we're at that level, you see, this consciousness feels its presence within the mind.

170
00:17:27,709 --> 00:17:35,278
A good example of that is when you're watching TV and you can see yourself in the screen watching TV.

171
00:17:35,680 --> 00:17:40,145
Now you can decide, are you going to watch TV or watch yourself watching TV?

172
00:17:41,688 --> 00:17:44,932
But as you're watching TV, you're aware of that thing.

173
00:17:45,032 --> 00:17:46,094
So there's a slippage.

174
00:17:46,434 --> 00:17:57,789
There's moments of consciousness which are absorbed in the TV program, but also switching over to this image that you see of yourself in the television screen.

175
00:17:58,171 --> 00:17:59,412
So it's oscillating like that.

176
00:18:01,295 --> 00:18:04,219
That's what's happening when we are

177
00:18:04,772 --> 00:18:17,270
very much self-aware of being the onlooker, the witness, the feeler, the experiencer of what it is we're actually experiencing whether it's a pain, an emotion, a sound, something we're looking at.

178
00:18:19,993 --> 00:18:27,124
That's why in a meditation there's always this accent of bringing ourselves back into the present moment.

179
00:18:27,144 --> 00:18:33,192
The immediate present moment which isn't any longer than a millisecond, if that.

180
00:18:33,832 --> 00:18:36,055
And that's what we mean by this concentration.

181
00:18:36,976 --> 00:18:40,740
Now whenever you say to somebody concentration, you always get this tension.

182
00:18:41,141 --> 00:18:42,603
You've got to concentrate.

183
00:18:42,623 --> 00:18:44,405
Knitted forehead.

184
00:18:44,445 --> 00:18:48,590
I remember as a kid getting a cough on the back of the head because you weren't concentrating.

185
00:18:50,513 --> 00:18:51,694
This idea of force.

186
00:18:52,876 --> 00:18:57,142
But actually concentration comes about mainly through interest.

187
00:18:58,503 --> 00:19:01,627
Did you have any problem with concentration when you were interested in something?

188
00:19:03,076 --> 00:19:03,916
It doesn't arise, does it?

189
00:19:04,438 --> 00:19:08,765
If you're interested, there's an immediate giving of oneself to what you're actually doing.

190
00:19:10,287 --> 00:19:15,536
So, in our meditation, again, there is this wanting to know.

191
00:19:15,556 --> 00:19:19,221
I mean, that's the essence of this Buddha mind within us.

192
00:19:19,701 --> 00:19:20,644
It wants to know.

193
00:19:20,663 --> 00:19:29,758
And that wanting to know, if you join into it, will draw you into the investigation of things that are arising and passing away.

194
00:19:30,903 --> 00:19:37,169
And that in itself is strong enough to actually make us focus in and in to a single point.

195
00:19:38,609 --> 00:19:55,666
But when that single point appears, very occasionally, virtually impossible on a weekend retreat, I'm sorry to say, although I wanted to see you are good enough probably to get there, there is that single point where there isn't time for that reflection.

196
00:19:57,769 --> 00:19:59,931
And those are the moments of pure vipassana.

197
00:20:00,366 --> 00:20:07,217
And those are the moments when this consciousness is experiencing itself in its purity.

198
00:20:09,799 --> 00:20:17,590
And at that point, to confuse matters, the object-subject relationship collapses.

199
00:20:18,471 --> 00:20:20,595
There's no object and there's no subject.

200
00:20:20,615 --> 00:20:23,700
There's just that direct experience.

201
00:20:23,720 --> 00:20:26,683
We get it occasionally in our lives as adults.

202
00:20:26,763 --> 00:20:28,145
It's very difficult for us to get that.

203
00:20:28,817 --> 00:20:55,010
it's like you'll get it for instance just for a moment when you trap your finger in the door there's just a single moment there of pure pain and there's nobody experiencing it it's only the moment afterwards that you say oh my thumb just that moment of absolute pure stillness within the present moment so

204
00:20:55,413 --> 00:21:23,934
When you're meditating, you see and you're watching the rising and falling of the breath and you're looking at its quality of transience you're looking at the quality of its process what you're trying to do is to see it more and more closely so that you begin to break up the idea that somebody's breathing that there is anything else that there is anything called a breath that's only a mental idea

205
00:21:24,926 --> 00:21:31,715
And that all there is are minute moments of sensations arising into consciousness.

206
00:21:33,117 --> 00:21:46,654
And it's from these minute moments of sensations that the mind is able to build up a concept whereby you can hold a certain length of time within which you call it the in-breath or the out-breath.

207
00:21:47,096 --> 00:21:48,738
And that's all mentation.

208
00:21:49,018 --> 00:21:50,240
That's all done in the mind.

209
00:21:50,759 --> 00:21:54,444
The only thing that's actually happening in terms of input

210
00:21:54,948 --> 00:21:58,372
are these little sparky moments of sensations.

211
00:22:01,276 --> 00:22:07,544
And to get down at that level is to deconstruct the way we construct the world around us.

212
00:22:08,224 --> 00:22:15,595
It's to begin to see that everything that we experience is being totally, completely manufactured by the mind.

213
00:22:16,875 --> 00:22:17,176
Everything.

214
00:22:18,778 --> 00:22:20,601
Even this room

215
00:22:20,917 --> 00:22:26,544
you wouldn't doubt the objective existence of this room in a sense that if we all left, the room would disappear.

216
00:22:27,365 --> 00:22:32,730
The room has, in a sense, its own being, using that word very loosely.

217
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:38,057
But when we walk into this room, there aren't as many rooms as there are people here.

218
00:22:40,118 --> 00:22:42,582
Because each of us experience the room in our own way.

219
00:22:44,824 --> 00:22:50,250
So in this sense, you see, we're living in a world which is completely mind-made.

220
00:22:51,057 --> 00:23:00,846
This dukkha that we're looking at, one of the ways that the Buddha talks about it is loke dukkha, dukkha nirodha.

221
00:23:00,866 --> 00:23:08,694
It's in this world that there is this suffering, this unpleasantness, whatever, and there is an end to it in this world.

222
00:23:09,174 --> 00:23:15,181
And when he defines in this world, he defines it as this body, mind and heart.

223
00:23:15,201 --> 00:23:19,005
In his terms, it would have been, for those of you who know, the five aggregates.

224
00:23:22,816 --> 00:23:51,777
so this whole world that we're living in which has no doubt an objective existence outside us is recreated by us and we have to live in it we have to live within that creation now what we do of course is to project all our ways of looking onto the world we're living in and if that projection is wrong if that projection is unwholesome, unskillful

225
00:23:52,127 --> 00:23:55,451
then it's not surprising that the world should mirror that back to us.

226
00:24:01,258 --> 00:24:07,324
So, for instance, if I have an angry disposition, I shouldn't be surprised that people should get angry with me.

227
00:24:09,586 --> 00:24:10,948
Because I'm exciting in them.

228
00:24:10,968 --> 00:24:15,232
There's a resonance between us, isn't there?

229
00:24:15,617 --> 00:24:20,143
Even though there's no direct contact within our emotions, there's a resonance.

230
00:24:20,282 --> 00:24:23,988
So we can feel another person's emotions against our own hearts.

231
00:24:25,308 --> 00:24:28,952
So if I go into a situation angry, that resonates.

232
00:24:29,473 --> 00:24:31,717
So everybody comes back at me angry.

233
00:24:31,737 --> 00:24:34,359
Or fearful, or run away, which is preferred.

234
00:24:41,548 --> 00:24:43,329
So this...

235
00:24:46,938 --> 00:24:52,665
this unwholesome place that we found ourselves in, is slowly being manufactured by us.

236
00:24:53,446 --> 00:24:59,134
The first of it is to do with this wrong view, this me, this mind.

237
00:24:59,173 --> 00:25:00,256
That's where its root is.

238
00:25:01,017 --> 00:25:15,155
Now, if you really think that this body is what you are, taking it at that absolute basic level, if you think this body is what you are, then two things, isn't there?

239
00:25:15,336 --> 00:25:16,017
First of all,

240
00:25:16,739 --> 00:25:21,143
It has to be protected at all costs.

241
00:25:21,163 --> 00:25:22,664
That's the first basic thing, isn't it?

242
00:25:22,924 --> 00:25:24,566
That's what we want from our government.

243
00:25:24,586 --> 00:25:26,048
We want safety first.

244
00:25:27,368 --> 00:25:32,334
Prosperity next, but you definitely want safety first.

245
00:25:32,354 --> 00:25:34,576
So we try to make the world safe.

246
00:25:34,935 --> 00:25:37,558
Safe at all levels.

247
00:25:37,578 --> 00:25:39,980
That safety, of course, overreaches itself.

248
00:25:40,500 --> 00:25:44,724
And we feel far more safe with a million pounds in the bank than 10,000.

249
00:25:45,326 --> 00:25:46,527
Or than none, definitely.

250
00:25:47,974 --> 00:25:50,577
So there's that accumulation, that greed.

251
00:25:51,019 --> 00:25:53,622
And that greed steps into other people's territory.

252
00:25:55,324 --> 00:26:08,540
You can see how the world, especially at the moment, through our economic system, is just constantly trying to fill this gap, this lack, this feeling of any minute now something terrible could happen.

253
00:26:09,742 --> 00:26:12,026
So I have to surround myself with security.

254
00:26:13,007 --> 00:26:17,813
Consider, consider the amount of money spent on insurance.

255
00:26:20,189 --> 00:26:21,630
all through fear.

256
00:26:21,650 --> 00:26:32,579
And silly things like, you know, that council that wanted all those flowers taken away from lampposts in case they fell on somebody's head, which they hadn't done for 1,500 years.

257
00:26:33,540 --> 00:26:35,001
Now, of course, it may happen, who knows?

258
00:26:35,702 --> 00:26:38,566
And it would have meant some sort of compensation, the fear.

259
00:26:40,606 --> 00:26:49,015
So this self that we have, this idea of self in the body, seeking safety means that subconsciously

260
00:26:49,332 --> 00:26:50,933
it lives in a state of fear.

261
00:26:53,777 --> 00:26:56,740
So the root emotion of the self is fear.

262
00:26:57,923 --> 00:27:00,244
And we touch that when death approaches us.

263
00:27:00,306 --> 00:27:02,347
We touch that fear when death approaches us.

264
00:27:05,412 --> 00:27:17,787
Now, once we have the understanding that the more I accumulate, the safer I feel, then of course anything which approaches that safety from a negative point of view is seen as an enemy.

265
00:27:18,931 --> 00:27:22,015
You get your aversion, you get your pushing away.

266
00:27:22,715 --> 00:27:27,142
And of course if you can't, if what you're pushing away is too big, then you run for it.

267
00:27:27,883 --> 00:27:36,375
So that fight-flight syndrome is the other side of the self, presuming always that this is what I am.

268
00:27:38,497 --> 00:27:46,288
Through the process of our insight, as we disengage from that, as we deconstruct all that sort of wrong understanding,

269
00:27:48,563 --> 00:28:17,592
the fear lessens you begin to live in a more benign world now there comes a point through the process of awakening when a person knows quite distinctly that they're not this body so the fully liberated person has no doubt whatsoever they know they're not the body so you can see if you now are absolutely certain within yourself through your personal experience that you are not the body

270
00:28:18,922 --> 00:28:26,690
What can frighten you?

271
00:28:26,710 --> 00:28:32,576
And that's really why we say that the liberated person doesn't have any fear, can't have fear.

272
00:28:32,596 --> 00:28:42,326
There's nothing there to be fearful about.

273
00:28:42,346 --> 00:28:46,431
Now, how do we begin to undermine that sense of self, you see?

274
00:28:46,900 --> 00:28:55,692
First of all, it's to use that technique of distancing within our meditation where noting something is like pointing at it.

275
00:28:55,713 --> 00:29:01,442
So when you've got a pain in the knee, if you say, pain, pain, you're already distancing from it.

276
00:29:01,461 --> 00:29:04,567
You have to be careful with that technique because it might be a way of pushing it away.

277
00:29:04,586 --> 00:29:05,448
You know, pain, pain.

278
00:29:06,670 --> 00:29:09,875
It's more like an acknowledgement, a clear acknowledgement.

279
00:29:09,894 --> 00:29:14,982
And once you've steadied yourself to go towards it, to plunge into the experience of it,

280
00:29:15,875 --> 00:29:18,679
Same with our emotions, no matter how painful they are.

281
00:29:19,319 --> 00:29:23,686
To distance for a moment and say, this is an emotional state, whatever it might be.

282
00:29:24,147 --> 00:29:26,471
Despair, all that sort of stuff.

283
00:29:27,593 --> 00:29:43,096
And then once you've gained that equanimity, once you've gained that position of courage to go into the emotion and to stay there and just watch it as feeling, just as sensations.

284
00:29:44,696 --> 00:29:48,300
If we can stay at that level, you see, it loses its name.

285
00:29:49,101 --> 00:29:52,023
Despair is just an awful sickly feeling.

286
00:29:52,345 --> 00:29:55,106
Fear is just an awful sickly feeling.

287
00:29:55,126 --> 00:29:56,888
And you can stay there with it.

288
00:29:56,909 --> 00:30:01,053
And all the time, you're just allowing this state, what is it?

289
00:30:01,272 --> 00:30:01,814
An energy.

290
00:30:01,953 --> 00:30:04,557
That's all it is, a turbulence.

291
00:30:04,576 --> 00:30:06,778
To express itself.

292
00:30:06,798 --> 00:30:12,584
All these emotional states, remember, all they're saying is, you know, listen to me, I'm very afraid.

293
00:30:12,944 --> 00:30:13,184
Help.

294
00:30:14,650 --> 00:30:16,672
They only want to tell you how they feel.

295
00:30:17,792 --> 00:30:18,273
That's all.

296
00:30:20,596 --> 00:30:29,644
And to allow that to happen is the process of liberating ourselves through understanding dukkha, through understanding suffering.

297
00:30:31,507 --> 00:30:43,459
So, the distancing allows us to understand that this is not me, not mine, undermining that fundamental position that we have, that this is me, I am a human being, right?

298
00:30:44,384 --> 00:31:13,884
am in a sense of continuous, continual am in a sense of forever there's this feeling that you're never actually going to die everybody else does but it might happen tomorrow so it's that case of undermining that and then of going into what you're being presented with to actually see how we create the suffering so how do we create these mental states so that's when we begin to discover

299
00:31:14,084 --> 00:31:42,183
this split of indulging and suppressing indulging and suppressing indulging and suppressing that process of psychology which is called in Buddhism the wheel of dependent origination sometimes they call it interdependent origination is

300
00:31:42,568 --> 00:31:44,751
the psychological teaching of the Buddha.

301
00:31:45,352 --> 00:31:53,281
And as far as I've read from people who should know better than me, it was completely new within Indian literature.

302
00:31:53,442 --> 00:31:57,768
There was nothing like that sort of psychology until the Buddha came.

303
00:32:00,090 --> 00:32:06,838
And the Buddha begins with this lovely word, avijja, which means not knowing.

304
00:32:09,643 --> 00:32:12,306
So this consciousness that we've been talking about

305
00:32:13,011 --> 00:32:14,953
begins from a position of not knowing.

306
00:32:16,836 --> 00:32:22,121
Sometimes it's translated as ignorance, but that gives it a sort of pejorative, heavy, you know, like you're stupid.

307
00:32:22,642 --> 00:32:24,002
But it's not that, you just don't know.

308
00:32:24,022 --> 00:32:28,327
And from this not knowing, it begins to build up a world.

309
00:32:30,450 --> 00:32:39,558
So this world is built up around the middle part, where we experience the world as pleasant or unpleasant, and then we try to that accumulation.

310
00:32:40,535 --> 00:32:51,724
Now that process of accumulation, that process of attachment, that process of holding on to things, grasping on to things, that's what's meant by this word desire.

311
00:32:52,645 --> 00:32:57,529
And unfortunately that word desire covers also desires that we ought to have.

312
00:32:58,151 --> 00:33:04,336
Desires such as wanting to meditate continuously.

313
00:33:04,355 --> 00:33:05,998
So you have to be careful with that word desire.

314
00:33:06,038 --> 00:33:09,681
Sometimes it's translated as craving, which is over the top.

315
00:33:09,998 --> 00:33:12,901
It's desires which arise from a wrong view of self.

316
00:33:16,805 --> 00:33:36,644
And what we build up, the picture of the world that we build up and live in, in this uncomfortable way, you see, when you hit the root, when you hit the root of this not-self, when you begin to see it's not me, not mine, you're actually taking away the foundation.

317
00:33:37,664 --> 00:33:39,346
So the whole pack of cars just falls.

318
00:33:41,150 --> 00:33:44,993
It's not a case of having to go back step by step.

319
00:33:45,575 --> 00:33:48,979
It's as soon as you see something, the whole delusion collapses.

320
00:33:50,721 --> 00:34:02,153
So for instance, if somebody were to come up on the street and give you a kick in the butt, and then you turn around and they ran off, you might go away thinking, you know, that's the worst thing that's ever happened to me in my life.

321
00:34:02,334 --> 00:34:03,695
You know, how could anybody do that?

322
00:34:03,715 --> 00:34:05,637
And you'd be angry and furious.

323
00:34:06,022 --> 00:34:11,887
And then you read in the evening news that it was somebody who'd lost their bottle and was going around kicking people in the butt.

324
00:34:12,548 --> 00:34:16,092
And they suddenly think, oh, well, the guy was a lunatic.

325
00:34:16,112 --> 00:34:17,512
Suddenly, everything's forgiven.

326
00:34:18,393 --> 00:34:20,394
He's just gone off his rocker.

327
00:34:21,715 --> 00:34:26,039
There's a sudden forgiveness, all because of a change of understanding, a change of view.

328
00:34:27,041 --> 00:34:28,061
So that's all we're doing.

329
00:34:28,161 --> 00:34:31,023
We're trying to undercut the original view we had.

330
00:34:31,364 --> 00:34:35,608
And in so doing, this whole pack of cards just begins to crumble.

331
00:34:38,288 --> 00:34:41,833
The third view, so the first is that seeing of not-self.

332
00:34:41,893 --> 00:34:49,623
The second is trying to understand how we create this suffering through attachment, through grasping, through aversion, through suppression.

333
00:34:50,324 --> 00:34:54,028
The third view is to see the transience of things.

334
00:34:54,048 --> 00:35:01,097
To see that everything that we're experiencing is only here for this millisecond and it disappears.

335
00:35:03,221 --> 00:35:04,902
And that's where we get, that's

336
00:35:05,068 --> 00:35:07,452
You can see that most in the breath.

337
00:35:07,811 --> 00:35:11,315
That's why we always begin with the breath as a certain position.

338
00:35:11,456 --> 00:35:15,161
First of all, it's always there, or you've got problems.

339
00:35:16,742 --> 00:35:24,110
And secondly, because of its movement, especially in the belly, especially in the abdomen, it's rising and falling.

340
00:35:24,130 --> 00:35:32,240
And just to stay with that flow, just to stay with that wave of rising and falling, and if you can, to feel how delicious it is,

341
00:35:33,148 --> 00:35:35,411
They're very subtle, gentle sensations.

342
00:35:36,873 --> 00:35:42,521
We always live on this high point of wanting sensation, our sensational life to be sensational.

343
00:35:43,943 --> 00:35:48,891
We're always living at that point where we ought to be in a state of gross happiness, jumping up and down.

344
00:35:50,072 --> 00:35:57,822
And the point is that there's a much deeper and a much more subtle and a much more gratifying happiness to be found in peace.

345
00:36:00,757 --> 00:36:05,661
And that peace is measured or is found in the body in these neutral sensations.

346
00:36:07,443 --> 00:36:11,827
Just a state of contentment with just a simple, neutral feeling.

347
00:36:12,987 --> 00:36:15,789
And as you get into that, you'll see there's a lovely loveliness there.

348
00:36:16,811 --> 00:36:19,713
Now, you can go down to the river here, you see.

349
00:36:19,753 --> 00:36:21,394
Now, that river isn't exciting.

350
00:36:21,976 --> 00:36:24,117
It's probably one of the most boring rivers.

351
00:36:26,519 --> 00:36:27,960
It just flows and it's flat.

352
00:36:28,240 --> 00:36:30,222
There's no ripples, I mean, on this little corner here.

353
00:36:30,693 --> 00:36:39,262
There's no ripples, there's nothing, it's just this glass plate which continually changes just slightly catching the shades of light.

354
00:36:40,322 --> 00:36:48,311
And if you watch, if you keep your mind on that and just keep watching it, you'll catch its peace.

355
00:36:48,331 --> 00:36:55,338
And it's trying to use nature like that or just the starkness of the trees, just the blueness of the sky which never changes in a sense.

356
00:36:56,320 --> 00:36:58,422
And just to see that there's a real

357
00:36:58,739 --> 00:37:05,626
A deeper sense of contentment and happiness in stillness, in quiet, in silence.

358
00:37:05,646 --> 00:37:12,376
In fact, one of the epithets of Nibbana is the noble silence.

359
00:37:12,396 --> 00:37:16,420
Now, when we watch the breath and we're beginning to see actually that that's just a concept.

360
00:37:17,621 --> 00:37:20,005
You can't see the belly, you can't see the air.

361
00:37:20,224 --> 00:37:21,726
All you have is sensations.

362
00:37:21,847 --> 00:37:26,291
And from these little building blocks of little sensations, the mind builds up a concept.

363
00:37:26,753 --> 00:37:28,375
The stomachs are rising and falling

364
00:37:28,878 --> 00:37:30,840
or the air is coming in and out of your nose.

365
00:37:33,184 --> 00:37:39,293
And there's an image there, you can see your nose, or you can see somewhere in your mind, your belly.

366
00:37:41,197 --> 00:37:44,021
But behind that, there are just these sensations.

367
00:37:44,041 --> 00:37:55,358
And it's cutting through that, through this process of just looking, just focusing, drawn by interest, that we begin to experience that in fact life is extraordinarily momentary.

368
00:37:56,434 --> 00:38:03,423
Now what's the effect on our psychology when we realize that everything is extraordinarily momentary?

369
00:38:03,443 --> 00:38:08,269
Well, there's nothing worth holding on to.

370
00:38:08,289 --> 00:38:09,431
There's an immediate release.

371
00:38:09,532 --> 00:38:14,197
There's an immediate stopping of trying to grasp things, keep things as they are.

372
00:38:15,278 --> 00:38:17,963
It's a relief.

373
00:38:17,983 --> 00:38:24,231
And one of the things that the Buddha says, which we read out in our little opening ceremony, the taste

374
00:38:24,565 --> 00:38:27,329
of Nibbana is the taste of freedom.

375
00:38:28,271 --> 00:38:30,474
It's the liberation from, it's the relief.

376
00:38:33,599 --> 00:38:45,998
Every time you get that little sense of relief, of letting go, of just letting be, in all these little pat phrases that you get, these are little touches of Nibbana.

377
00:38:49,643 --> 00:38:52,969
Tomorrow, I hope I remind you, I probably will forget, as usual,

378
00:38:53,809 --> 00:39:03,047
But when you're eating, you see, there's a distinction to be made, these are just my own distinctions of words, between satisfaction and contentment.

379
00:39:03,067 --> 00:39:11,481
So if you want satisfaction, you keep eating until you feel satisfied, until you feel completely full, bloated, and you think that's enough, and then you go and have a sleep.

380
00:39:13,786 --> 00:39:16,931
Now, if you practice your meditation when you're eating,

381
00:39:17,536 --> 00:39:22,081
And you can feel that draw of greed just for that extra toast.

382
00:39:23,061 --> 00:39:25,605
We're promised toast tomorrow.

383
00:39:25,625 --> 00:39:28,347
Just for that extra piece of toast and marmalade.

384
00:39:29,047 --> 00:39:31,851
And you wait and you know that this is not necessary.

385
00:39:33,632 --> 00:39:35,295
This is overeating.

386
00:39:36,036 --> 00:39:37,777
Bad for the body.

387
00:39:37,797 --> 00:39:40,681
Producing early death.

388
00:39:40,701 --> 00:39:42,342
Toast can be lethal.

389
00:39:43,443 --> 00:39:44,724
Taken in vast quantities.

390
00:39:47,623 --> 00:39:51,807
Once you see that, now hold on, this is greed.

391
00:39:52,148 --> 00:39:53,690
And you just hold on in there.

392
00:39:54,351 --> 00:39:55,492
And you let the greed come.

393
00:39:55,751 --> 00:39:56,432
This wolf.

394
00:39:58,255 --> 00:40:01,518
Marmalade after all.

395
00:40:01,538 --> 00:40:03,539
And you just wait for the wolf to die.

396
00:40:03,579 --> 00:40:04,800
To die, you see.

397
00:40:05,181 --> 00:40:09,965
There will come a point where there's no desire in the mind.

398
00:40:11,507 --> 00:40:13,028
That's contentment.

399
00:40:13,048 --> 00:40:14,931
That is a taste of nirvana.

400
00:40:16,396 --> 00:40:24,025
So it's not as though nibbana or this awakened state is something which is totally transcendent from what we actually can experience here and now.

401
00:40:24,686 --> 00:40:26,668
It's something that we can get little bites of.

402
00:40:27,469 --> 00:40:36,259
But you have to acknowledge it because this consciousness does not know that this is actually a better place than satisfaction.

403
00:40:36,278 --> 00:40:39,061
It's driven by everything in this society.

404
00:40:40,003 --> 00:40:45,610
The whole of our industry, the whole of our advertising is driven to satisfaction.

405
00:40:47,885 --> 00:41:00,797
And it's only when you begin to realize that that place actually produces more desire, more greed, a non-end to it, a churning of it, that you begin to realize there must be a better place than this.

406
00:41:01,878 --> 00:41:04,141
And that's it.

407
00:41:04,161 --> 00:41:10,967
Now, you can't get there without enduring happily, joyously, the suffering.

408
00:41:13,490 --> 00:41:15,693
That suffering is not the suffering of hell.

409
00:41:15,952 --> 00:41:17,014
That's not going to get worse.

410
00:41:17,668 --> 00:41:20,411
That's the suffering of purgatory.

411
00:41:20,431 --> 00:41:22,934
That's the suffering of purging.

412
00:41:22,954 --> 00:41:26,539
I was brought up a Catholic and we had these three distinctive realms.

413
00:41:27,139 --> 00:41:29,161
Hell, purgatory and heaven.

414
00:41:30,402 --> 00:41:31,583
Hell, you were stuck.

415
00:41:32,224 --> 00:41:35,467
You couldn't get out of that one.

416
00:41:35,487 --> 00:41:38,731
Couldn't even get a drop of water from heaven.

417
00:41:38,751 --> 00:41:47,001
Purgatory was a transient state where you went through these sufferings in order to attain the final glory of heaven.

418
00:41:48,989 --> 00:41:55,434
Now, in terms of whether these actually exist or not is not a particular consequence to us here and now.

419
00:41:55,856 --> 00:41:57,757
But in terms of mental states, definitely.

420
00:41:59,860 --> 00:42:09,889
Those mental states that we enter where we see no end to it, the despairs, the sudden impossibility of life, all that, that's hell.

421
00:42:09,909 --> 00:42:14,793
Purgatory are those states of mind where we're quite happy to suffer because we know there's an end to it.

422
00:42:16,411 --> 00:42:23,081
So our meditation is 99.999% purgatory.

423
00:42:27,788 --> 00:42:37,202
I hold out no great hope for sudden or swift liberation.

424
00:42:37,222 --> 00:42:40,887
And neither did the Buddha.

425
00:42:40,907 --> 00:42:45,675
He said it was a gradual path and I shall leave you with this quote.

426
00:42:46,347 --> 00:42:53,135
somebody comes to him and says, listen, this training you've got to be doing, very hard, very painful, very awful.

427
00:42:54,297 --> 00:42:55,619
And the Buddha said, well, yes, it is.

428
00:42:56,159 --> 00:43:00,184
But, you know, you just keep going and you'll attain Nibbana.

429
00:43:01,045 --> 00:43:03,188
And the reply was, Nibbana, so what?

430
00:43:04,449 --> 00:43:09,516
And he says, well, when you get to Nibbana, you are contented and with it happy.

431
00:43:10,898 --> 00:43:14,682
And he's describing his own state of mind, contented and with it happy.

